1 QUEST~
#General~
#END~
quest <difficulty> <mission> <size> <mob count>
quest <simple/easy/easy-medium/medium/medium-hard/hard>
quest status
quest fail
    difficulty 1-13     mission slaughter gauntlet
    size 1-6            mob count 1-6
     
Welcome to the quest system.  The Rafermand quest system is a fully automated,
random area/mob/object generation system.  By selecting from the different
variables above a quest will be loaded and you can go enjoy the killing or
being killed.  The first command available is used to manually set the
variables for a quest.  Difficulty ranges from 1-13.  Typically, a single
quest will not go over a difficulty of 10 (11-13 is reserved for 3-6 parties
of very experienced players).  Many of the mobs in the 11-13 are equivalant
of Tier 1 mobs and instead of having them for bosses they are wandering around
as regular mobs.  However, as with the risk the rewards from these mobs are of
course the best.  Difficulty 13 offers some of the best equipment in the game.

Missions are different missions you need to complete to get qps.  Besides the
fun of getting spoints (HELP SPOINTS) from killing tons of mobs, you will
also get QPS for completing the mission in a certain amount of time.  QPS can
be spent on getting your corpse out of a quest if you don't want to wait for
it to end (HELP MORGUE) or better it can be spend on equipment only available
through spending QPS.  As of this writing the only mission available is slaughter.
Slaughter is a mission where you have to slaughter most of the mobs loaded.

Size is the actual size of the dungeon.  1 is the smallest dungeon and consists
of 50 rooms.  6 is the largest consisting of 300 rooms.  It is a good idea to
pick something that matches how much time you have to spend on the quest and
the amount of QPS you are hoping to get (more on that later)

Mob Count is simply the amount of mobs in the dungeon.  1 is the lowest rate (below
1 per room) and 6 is around 3 per room.  This might not sound like a lot, but
the mobs wander and you can see 3-4 times that in one room.

(CONTINUE ON WITH QUEST2)
(Quest Obj is covered in QUEST4)
~

1 QUEST2~
#General~
#END~
The second command is used if you want a quest generated for you based on your
sworth (HELP SWORTH).  This can give you an idea on a difficulty to select if
you do not know what to try.  The easiest settings pick a difficulty rating
you should be easily capable of handling and it loads a small zone along with
a small amount of mobs.  The higher settings load a much more difficulty zone
but it keeps the amount of mobs and rooms to that of a middle-difficulty quest.

Next is the status command.  This shows you the status of the quest that you
are in and shows you the QPS/Wins/Losses you have accumulated.  A quest goes
through 3 stages.  The first is the travel time.  You have 20 minutes before
the quest will actually begin.  Once any member of your party (more on that)
enters the quest officially begins.  Once the quest is won or lost you have
25 minutes to hunt down the boss or get out.  After 25 minutes any corpses
in the quest will be moved to the morgue and the players will be moved to the
entrance of the quest (along with your mount).  

Lastly, the fail command fails a quest rather you have actually started it or
not.  Only the leader of the quest can fail it, so keep that in mind when you
choose the person to actually get the quest.

As mentioned before, you can bring a group into the quest.  You have to have
the group before hand because the quest data is stored on the players that
begin the quest.  You will not be able to bring outside help into your quest so
it is important to get them involve before you go in not after.  Adding group
members does increase the difficulty of a dungeon, but it also increases the
yield of the dungeon along with the QPS.  Also, you cannot start a quest with
6 and then intend to get all the QPS.  QPS are assigned before the quest and
reguardless of who is left, you get that cut of the QPS.  Lastly, you can only
have a party that is close in sworth.  This means the highest member cannot
have 2 times more sworth than the lowest member.  You will be told this before
starting a quest.

NOTE:  If all your party has 150k or more sworth, the Sworth rule does not apply.

(CONTINE ON with QUEST3)
~

1 QUEST3~
#General~
#END~
As mentioned QPS are assigned before a quest.  QPS are generated based on the
difficulty of the quest, the number of rooms in it, the number of mobs, and
the number of players involved.  Picking the smallest amount of mobs and rooms
will get you a greatly reduced number of QPS than compared to picking something
in the middle.  QPS are only assigned on wins and cannot be transfered.  QPS
can only be won if you are present in the quest zone when the win happens.  If
you go LD or you are dead when they finish you will get not QPS, so keep this
in mind, you need your whole party there or they miss out.  (NOTE:  You are
considered still logged in if you are LD.  If you are LD in the actual quest zone
you will get the points)

The quest zones themselves only stay in memory as long as there is no copyover,
reboot, or crash.  There will be no reimbursement on anything eaten by this unless
it is a corpse (which should be moved to limbo and retreivable by an imm).

Lastly, there are some mob information you should know.  First, a boss mob will
only spawn in a 100 room or better quest (this is a size of 2 or better).  The
captain mobs only spawn 1 per 50 rooms (So only a captain spawns in a size 1).  Both
of these mobs are more difficult than the normal mobs but they drop more ore
equipment/gold and also have a better chance of dropping quest equipment.  Next,
there is a "common" mob that loads close to half the time in each quest.  Lastly,
there is a limit on how much gold/ore equipment is loaded in the zone.  Just because
your common mob is a PC-race mob does not you will walk out with a TON of ore.

(CONTINUE to QUEST4 for coverage over the quest obj commands)
~

