1 SPHERE2 SPHERES2~
#Skills~
#Magic~
#Combat~
#END~
&w&GFollowing off with the last statement, Mage is done this way for a few reasons. Mages 
will find it difficult at first to master their craft. Tier 1 spells (help TIERS) are 
rather weak and do little damage and require mana that you simply do not have. It is much 
easier to take a trusty Steel weapon and bash a beast over the head with it, but it 
requires patiences and training to develop a good mage. In addition, this creates a bit 
of disbalance if you try to pick up other spheres with Mage. You will find yourself 
having difficult keeping them balanced because of the requires for the next Spheres 
compared to the requirements in the other spheres. Cleric is the second worst, but 
contains less than half of the spells available in the Mage sphere. When it comes to the 
other 3 spheres, they contain a bit less than the Cleric sphere, so you won't find 
yourself investing as much points into skills. However, you have automated skills in 
these 3 spheres that do not require you to physically use them, and other skills like 
attack skills (roundhouse) that you use over and over to inflict blows. You might not 
have a good balance of points in these spheres, but you will find them easier to learn. 
This can be both a good thing and a bad thing, depending on Sphere dominance. 

&w&WThe skill system distributes learning in two ways. First, it goes by spheres.&w&G 
This will take the percentage of points you have in each sphere and multiply it by the 
gain you get when you use a skill or spell. If 40 percent of your points are in Mage, 
when you use a Mage sphere spell, you will get 40 percent of the normal increase if you 
had 100 percent. This increase is what you see indicated by the * in &c&wskills 
magic&w&G. So, back to the first helpfile, this is why it takes 3 times longer because 
you are only getting 33 percent a pop. If you had something like 45 45 10, you would get 
45 percent in one, 45 percent in the other, and 10 percent in the last one. &w&RThis 
works as long as you do not have a dominant sphere. A dominant sphere is a sphere where 
you have the majority of total points in all skills/spells. This means if you have 220 
points combined from all skills/spells, and you have 111 points in Mage, Mage will be 
classified as your dominant sphere. &w&GThere are some pros/cons to this setup, and they 
are listed in the next helpfile. 

                      ---------Continued in Sphere3---------
~

1 SPHERE3 SPHERES3~
#Skills~
#Magic~
#Combat~
#END~
&w&GAs mentioned before, a dominant sphere is one with the majority of the points. You 
will find a lot of the time players will fall into this catagory if they are working with 
mage spells. It is possible to fall dominant into the other 4 spheres, but it gets 
difficult to go without some sort of spells. More skills will be introduced down the road 
for the other spheres to help balance some of this out, but for now, this is what we 
have. When you have a dominant sphere, instead of getting the 80 percent or so because 80 
percent of your points are in Mage, it starts to break things down Group by Group. If you 
spend all your points in Earth, you will get 100 percent of those spells in Earth. This 
is reguardless if you have 51 percent in Mage of 98 percent in Mage. However, this is 
where things start to get a little dirty. If you are split up 50 and 50 between Earth and 
Air you will get 65 percent in both groups. The formula for that is as follows. 30 + (.7 
* Percent). So 30 + (.7 * 50) = 65. You will get 65 percent in both groups. If you are 
33, 33, 33 in three groups, you get 53.7 in each group. This system allows you to get a 
minimum of 30 percent in any group no matter how many points you have in that group. In 
addition to this, spells/skills in your master sphere suffer 1/3 of loss in points from 
not using them. This decrease could be good or bad depending if you are trying to lose 
skills/spells in that sphere. Just have to always remember, this all works if you have a 
majority of points in one sphere. 

Lastly, it is important to remember a few "exception" rules that exist, and some are to 
your benefit. 

&w&R1. If you get no skills/spells in other spheres, you are considered a specialist and 
get 100 percent gain in all groups in that sphere. As soon as you gain another point 
outside the sphere, it is broken. You could do a sphere this way to gain quickly, but 
when you go to learn another sphere, you are going to be in for a rude awakening because 
you will find yourself below the 1 percent range on the other spheres. Use at your own 
risk. (Best used with constant grouping of specialized characters) 
    
2. If you don't have any skills/spells over 5 points or in Novice you will be in "Newbie 
mode". Newbie mode allows you to gain 100 percent if it is the majority sphere (or group 
if it is dominant sphere) or 70 percent if not. This will change as soon as you fall into 
5 points or novice in a skill/spell 
    
&w&GWell that is all for now, rest assured that you know this complex system, or atleast 
you have some idea now. 

&w&CSEE ALSO:  &w&WSKILLS   TIERS   LISTGROUPS   SKILLSCOMMAND   LEARN    MAGIC   ELEMENTS
~

1 SPHERES~
#Skills~
#Magic~
#Combat~
#END~
Rafermand's skill/spell system is broken down into sections called Spheres. As of the 
writing of this helpfiles, those 5 spheres are: Mage, Cleric, Hand-to-Hand, Thief, and 
Warrior. The spheres represent the basic 4 classes along with hand-to-hand combat. I 
could of chose names that didn't correspond to the classes, but I thought it would be 
easier for newbies to get the idea of what is involved in each Sphere. 

Along with the spheres there are groups. In Mage you have Fire, Earth, Water, Air, and 
Energy (help ELEMENTS help MAGIC). In Cleric you have the same 5 along with Divine. The 
other 3 spheres have their own unique groups as well. Groups are similiar spells that are 
grouped together for a certain purpose that will be explained later. For now, just 
remember that groups are the actual groupings of spells/skills under the sphere level. 

Now that you know what exactly a sphere is, lets look at why it is important to 
understand this information. The Rafermand skill system works on a unique system in which 
you can learn anything you want because of the lack of classes. However, in order to make 
this fair so you cannot master everything, the system counter-balanced. This roughly 
means if you take 3 spheres (say Warrior, Mage, Cleric) and spend the same amount of 
points (points are the points you have in say shield, like 2, shows up in skills magic) 
you will find it 3 times harder to learn in all 3 of those spheres instead of just 
learning in 1. In AD&&D you find that if you want to be a multi-class character you must 
absorb the experience base for both classes. This works the same way here. In order to 
learn all 3 of the spheres, you must invest the amount of time it would take to advance 3 
characters who are working on 1 sphere only. This only really works with 3 or more 
spheres and you keep the points equal. You will often find yourself with more points in 
Mage if you develop that sphere because of the abundance of spells in it. 

                      ---------Continued in Sphere2---------
~

