1 SWORTH~
#General~
#END~
Sworth is a value generated based on all the stats you have not including
your worth (gold/bank) and what equipment you have on you (for some obvious
reasons).  The formula is weighted more toward skill advancement than stat
advancement, but having both will not hurt you here.  Besides this value to
explain the strength of your character, it is used in other purposes.

1.  It controls the cut of Skill points you get when grouped.  You get a share
    of the cut based on your percent of SWorth in the group.  If you have 200
    SWorth and your friend has 100, you get 66 percent and your friend 33.
2.  It controls bonuses you get with being in a group.  A group gets bonus skill
    points as long as the lowest SWorth in the group is not more than half the
    the highest (so if you have a 200 150 170 the lowest you can take is a 100
    without losing your group cut).

Number 2 is mainly done to prevent a group of 8 with a 10,000 and a bunch of 100s
for the sole purpose of getting the 10k a lot more points.  Due ot the nature of
the cut, if you have a lot of lower SWorths they won't get much of anything and
you won't get any bonuses.
~

1 TALENT~
#General~
#END~
Syntax:  talent <skill/spell> spend <#stars>
Syntax:  talent <skill/spell> spend point
Syntax:  talent <skill/spell> available
Syntax:  talent <skill/spell> cost
Syntax:  talent <stat name> cost
Syntax:  talent <stat name> available
Syntax:  talent <stat name> spend <#stars>
Syntax:  talent <stat name> spend point
Syntax:  talent list [obtained]
Syntax:  talent purchase <number>

Talent is used to increase a skill, a stat, or spend spoints toward an
actual talent.  A talent is something such as increasing a max stat
value or a special skill that is available to everyone or simply your
race.  The first part of the syntax involves skills/spells.  You can
spend either a star (1/10 of a point) or a full point.  You can use
the available option to see how many stars and/or points you can
purchase and then you can use cost to see how much it will cost.

Next part is the stat section.  Same options here, only thing of note
is cost for stats are mainly dependant on your hp/mana.  As you gain
more and more it will cost you move to increase any of your stats.  Then
again, as you get more and more hp you should be getting more and more
spoints.

Lastly, the list and purchase arguments are for purchasing talents.  Talents
are as simple as increasing the cap (max) on a stat.  Each race has a certain
limit for each stat (humans can go all the way up the increase scale on all
stats, this is part of their racial bonus).  Without giving it all away, it
is like the starting value for a stat.  Ogres can max the scale on hp/str but
won't get very far in int/mana.  Fairies are the exact opposite.  Elves tend
to go up the scale well in all areas.  Dwarves do well in all areas as well
and Hobbits do well in dex/agi but are average in the other areas.  There
is an optional argument for list to show what talents you have purchased.
~

