-----------------------Below are for trading between towns--------------------------
Syntax: tradegoods town take <name of town> <item> <number>.
Syntax: tradegoods town give <name of town> <item> <number>.

Following command is used to trade resources between kingdoms or towns in your own kingdom.

In order to trade between kingdoms you need to first start a trading offer.  Once you start
a trade between another kingdom, you use set to make an offer of what you want and what
you are willing to give.  Once you have set the correct values, you can send it to the other
kingdom (you can remove a resource by setting it to 0).  Once it is send to the other kingdom
they can either accept it or set it to another value and send it back.  The trade will continue
as long as it doesn't surpass the 3 day time limit or if it is accepted or declined.  Once a
trade is sent, you cannot alter it.  If you make a mistake, you can decline it and start it
allover again.

You can use the tradegoods list comand to see all active trades.  The first two lines are rather
easy to figure out, the last line shows a few different things.  It looks like this

[1  ] Offering - [ ]Arcadia      Receiving - [X]Radakia       Sent[ ]   Side[Offering]

It shows the offering and receiving kingdom.  The X before their name indicated if they
have the resources available that they are offering.  The Send field indicates that it has
been sent to the other kingdom for accepting, and the side indicates who has the trade proposal
at this moment.

***NOTE*** Trades will not be undone because you made a mistake, make sure to check to see if you
have the correct offers before you send it.

The last two commands for town trading was moved from townvalues to this command.  It allows you
to tradegoods between two towns in your town.  Anyone can give resources to another town, but
only the king and number1 and number2 and take from a town.

Lastly, in order to use this command, the towns have to be connected.  In order to trade
between two kingdoms, the default towns of the kingdoms have to be connected via a road.
In order to trade between two towns the towns have to be connected via a road.
~

1 TRADEROUTES~
#Kingdoms Management~
#END~
Syntax:  traderoutes

Trading is a very important feature of intrakingdom management and trading
between other kingdoms.  In order to move goods back and forth between towns
they need to be connected via roads.  Traderoutes uses a route algorithm I
aquired for use for this system.  It will check if two points are connected
via a road.  The range is 70 rooms in any direction.  If the two points are
greater than 70 rooms, they are not considered connected (so keep that in mind
if you start connecting up your towns or a road between two trading kingdoms).

When it comes to connecting kingdoms, the route is calculated between the two
default towns.  If you want to trade between two kingdoms, it is probably best
for the kingdoms to set their default towns to the two towns closest to
eachother.  The system will not use a "hoping" system like town X is connected
to town Y and town Y is connected to town Z so town Z is connected to town X.  This
will not work, so you will have to make sure your default towns are directly
connected to eachother.

To trade between towns and kingdoms you use the command tradegoods (help TRADEGOODS)
~

