#General~
#END~
Trap set <obj> <charges> <type> <damlow> <damhi> <room> <difficulty> <toolkit> <onetime> <resetvalue> <toolnegate> <frag> <flags>
Trap set simple <obj> <charges> <type> <damlow> <damhi> <room> <flags>
Trap create
Trap show <uid/area name/all/reset/inv/loaded/notloaded/frag>
Trap apply <obj name> <uid>
Trap add <charges> <type> <dam low> <dam hi> <room> <difficulty> <toolkit> <onetime> <reset value> <toolnegate> <frag> <flags>
Trap delete <uid>
Trap edit <uid> <trap option> <value>

   Trap Option - charges, maxcharges, type, damlow, damhi, room, difficulty, toolkit,
                 onetime, resetvalue, toolnegate, frag, flags
                  
Trap command is the mother command of configuring and placing traps on objects.  Trap is
available for use for anyone that is of building level and can be used to apply traps to
any object that is in your area's assigned range.  Only the highest level immortals can
apply traps to objects that are not in his/her assigned range.  Unlike the old trap code,
a trap can exist on a single object, not inside of a container.  This allows for a variety
of methods for triggering a trap.  Also, an object that is stored on a character will save
any trap on it, so it will remain trapped till it is detrapped, runs out of charges, or
the trap blows up the object.  For more information over traps, lets continue to (HELP TRAP2)
~

7 TRAP 2~
#General~
#END~
~

3 TRAP2~
#General~
#END~
Trap set        - Creates and applies a trap to the object specified.  The trap is reset 
                  into the area and will fire when the object is reset.
Trap set simple - Only the important options, does the same thing as trap set.
Trap create     - Creates a trap, but does not apply it.  Can then apply the trap later
                  and set its options using trap edit
Trap show       - Shows all the traps.  Will discuss the options later.
Trap apply      - Applies a trap to an object.  This will install a reset for the trap
                  into the area that it belongs to.  Make sure to save/fold after doing
                  any applies
Trap add        - Same as trap set but it does not apply the trap to an object
Trap delete     - Deletes a trap along with any resets or applies.
Trap edit       - Used to edit any trap available

In short, you use trap set to create the trap and then apply a reset to that object.  You
use create or add to simply create the reset and apply it later.  Apply is used to apply
a trap reset to an object when a trap already exists.  A trap is armed on an object by
default everytime the object is reloaded (so if the object is not picked up from a room it
will not reset till a reboot or the object is purged).  The option of resetvalue can be
set to 1 to force it to rearm/recharge every time the area resets.

Note:  Using set or apply to an object in your inventory will set it as a personal
trap and will save that information on your pfile or to whomever the trap ends
up on.  There will be no reset installed this way.  Resets will be installed if
the obj is in any other state.

(SEE HELP TRAP3 for more info
~

3 TRAP3~
#General~
#END~
charges       - Number of remaining charges left.
maxcharges    - Maximum number of charges on the trap.  When the trap is rearmed/recharged it
                will be set to this value.
type          - See (HELP TRAPTYPES).  Explosion or Blade is common.  Only 1 type per trap
damlow        - Low amount of damage.
damhi         - High amount of damage.
room          - Default is 0.  Setting it to 1 will damage everything in the room.
difficulty    - Difficulty to detrap.  Range is 0 to 300.  Setting it to anything over 100
                will make it impossible to detrap without a toolkit.
toolkit       - See (HELP TOOLKIT).  Toolkits are used to disarm a trap.
onetime       - Default is 0.  Setting it to 1 will delete the trap/reset after it fires
                just once.
resetvalue    - Default is 0.  Setting it to 1 will rearm/recharge the trap every time the
                area resets (compared to every time the trapped object is loaded)
toolnegate    - Value the tool will negate from the difficulty.  It can be more or less
                than the difficulty.
frag          - Range is 0 - 100.  Anything over 0 gives a percent chance that the firing
                of the trap will destroy the trapped object.  Setting it to 100 is a 100
                percent chance, setting it to 1 is a 1 percent chance.
flags         - See (HELP TRAPFLAGS).                

Lastly, lets check out (HELP TRAP4) for more information over trap show options
~

